Cars Dataset - Using KMeans Clustering¶

The data concerns city-cycle fuel consumption in miles per gallon, to be predicted in terms of 3 multivalued discrete and 5 continuous attributes

# credit: https://www.kaggle.com/willkoehrsen/start-here-a-gentle-introduction. 
# One of the best notebooks on getting started with a ML problem.

def missing_values_table(df):
        # Total missing values
        mis_val = df.isnull().sum()
        
        # Percentage of missing values
        mis_val_percent = 100 * df.isnull().sum() / len(df)
        
        # Make a table with the results
        mis_val_table = pd.concat([mis_val, mis_val_percent], axis=1)
        
        # Rename the columns
        mis_val_table_ren_columns = mis_val_table.rename(
        columns = {0 : 'Missing Values', 1 : '% of Total Values'})
        
        # Sort the table by percentage of missing descending
        "There are " + str(mis_val_table_ren_columns.shape[0]) +    " columns that have missing values."
        
        # Return the dataframe with missing information
        return mis_val_table_ren_columns

Findings on independent variables distribution¶

Acc is only predictor which appears to be distributed normally¶
Cylinder, disp,wt and hp looks to be distributed normally but are skewed and are multimodal(3 peaks)¶

Target variable mpg is having normal distribution and negatively correlated with disp, hp and wt¶

In [42]:
wcss = []
cluster_range = range( 1,20)  
for num_clusters in cluster_range:
    kmeans = KMeans(num_clusters, n_init = 10, random_state = 0)
    kmeans.fit(cars_df_scaled)
    labels = kmeans.labels_                     # capture the cluster lables
    centroids = kmeans.cluster_centers_         # capture the centroids    
    wcss.append(kmeans.inertia_)

plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
plt.plot(range(1,20), wcss,marker = "o")
plt.title('The elbow method')
plt.xlabel('The number of clusters')
plt.ylabel('WCSS')
plt.show()

In [51]:
## Cluster1
cars_df_scaled1=cars_df_scaled[cars_df_scaled['group']==0]
# Model initialization
regression_model = LinearRegression()
X=cars_df_scaled1.iloc[:,:-2]
y=cars_df_scaled1['mpg']
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.30, random_state=1)
# Fit the data(train the model)
regression_model.fit(X_train, y_train)
# Predict
y_predicted = regression_model.predict(X_test)

# model evaluation
rmse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_predicted)
r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_predicted)

# printing values
print('Slope:' ,regression_model.coef_)
print('Intercept:', regression_model.intercept_)
print('Root mean squared error: ', rmse)
print('R2 score: ', r2)

Findings between Linear Regression on Individual clusters vs on whole cluster group¶

Linear Regression on Individiual clusters have less RMSE but R2 value is very low indicating it represents only less variance in data.

Applying a single model on full dataset has a better R2 score indicating it explains well the variance in the data even though RMSE value is high

Since RMSE values of individual clusters regression model is low those model are better fit than the regression model for the full dataset.¶

The prediction rate has improved when the model is considered for the full cluster than the individual clusters.¶
